I am going to really criticize Indian cricket fans and the film makers in this comment of mine. What is it about a cricket player called Sachin Tendulkar, who has scored more centuries and runs than any other cricketer, who pulls at the heartstrings of cricket fans across India? or What is it about a cricketer called MS Dhoni, who has been hailed as the most successful captain in India? Films like Sachin and Dhoni are made to capitalize on a formula where a single talented young cricketer earns his place in the Indian team and achieves celebrity status. In the movie, the team travels all around the world playing matches and in some crucial matches, the team finds itself in a situation where it has to win against all odds. This is when our celebrity cricketer comes to the grease and play some breath taking cricket. His fans, in India, wait for the nail biting finish when he wins the glorious cup for India. Indian flag waving patriotic cricket fans jump in joy before the TV and in the stadium. Part of the formula for the origins of this cricketing hero (in the movie) begins in a dusty playground where kids play barefoot. This is where he reveals his genius, much to the astonishment of his teammates, opponents, bystanders, coach etc. The movie makers cleverly set up the celebrity cricketer (Sachin or Dhoni) in a do or die situation in a match to provoke emotions, camaraderie between the two Indian batsmen (Sachin or Dhoni with another batsman at the bowlers end) who are shouldering a huge responsibility. The movie makers focus on emotional build-up of the audience by subconsciously connecting cricket to patriotism. On the other hand, movies like Sachin or Dhoni reveal no indication of the fact that cricket is just a sport and victory or defeat does mean the end of the world for India. The regard for viewing cricket as 'just a game' is completely pushed aside in such movies to show the celebrity cricketer's prowess. Every Indian must boycott such movies. They should understand that cricket is just a game and the movie makers are capitalising on the achievements of an individual cricketer. The movie makers have no role to play in the player's achievements or India's achievements in cricket. That is my point.

I saw this "emotion" today.. Its not a movie..or a cinema or a film.. It was living my childhood all over again.. The 17 or so years of my life.. It made me realise how much this PHENOMENON had influenced all our life.. I could remember  all those cut scenes of the matches as if it was yesterday.. I remember where i was on that day when the match was played... I recollected the people who were in the same room when i watched it.. 

It truly is an emotion... Something that cannot be said , written or explained.. but only felt.  I cried at few places... 

And as he walked out of the ground for the very last time... it was the end of an era... A Man, A Phenomenon, A GOD that carried the game of cricket for his nation... For 24 years.... Many would say otherwise...

But for Me and millions of other people He Defined the Beautiful Game of Cricket...

SRT TODAY TOMMOROW AND FOREVER......
.1. “Sachin Tendulkar has carried the burden of the nation for 21 years. It is time we carried him on our shoulders” – Virat Kohli after India won the 2011 World Cup
2. “I have seen God, he bats at no. 4 for India” – Matthew Hayden
3. I saw him playing on television and was struck by his technique, so I asked my wife to come look at him. Now I never saw myself play, but I felt that this player is playing with a style similar to mine, and she looked at him on Television and said yes, there is a similarity between the two…his compactness, technique, stroke production – it all seemed to gel! – Sir Donald Bradman
4. “I am fortunate that I’ve to bowl at him only in the nets!” – Anil Kumble
5. “We did not lose to a team called India. We lost to a man called Sachin” – Mark Taylor, during the test match in Chennai (1997)
6. “India me aap Prime Minister ko ek baar katghare me khada kar sakte hain. Par Sachin Tendulkar par ungli nahi utha Sakte.” – Navjot Singh Sidhu
7. Harder he works, the luckier he gets – Ian Chappell
8. I’ll be going to bed having nightmares of Sachin just running down the wicket and belting me back over the head for six. He was unstoppable. I don’t think anyone, apart from Don Bradman, is in the same class as Sachin Tendulkar. He is just an amazing player – Shane Warne
9. I think he is marvellous. I think he will fit in whatever category of Cricket that has been played or will be played, from the first ball that has ever been bowled to the last ball that’s going to be. He can play in any era and at any level. I would say he’s 99.5% perfect – Viv Richards on Sachin Tendulkar
10. Beneath the helmet, under that unruly curly hair, inside the cranium, there is something we don’t know, something beyond scientific measure. Something that allows him to soar, to roam a territory of sport that, forget us, even those who are gifted enough to play alongside him cannot even fathom. When he goes out to bat, people switch on their television sets and switch off their lives – BBC Sports, on Sachin Tendulkar
11. Twenty20 cricket is the dessert and you can’t survive on that. Who wants to eat only desserts? – Sachin Tendulkar on T20 cricket
12. He is a perfectly balanced batsman and knows perfectly well when to attack and when to play defensive cricket. He has developed the ability to treat bowlers all over the world with contempt and can destroy any attack with utmost ease – Greg Chappell
13. He has defined cricket in his fabulous, impeccable manner. He is to batting what Shane Warne is to bowling – Richie Benaud
14. India’s fortune will depend on how many runs the little champion scores. There is no doubt Tendulkar is the real thing – Sunil Gavaskar
15. “There are 2 kind of batsmen in the world. One Sachin Tendulkar. Two all the others” – Andy Flower
16. “Sachin Tendulkar has often reminded me of a veteran army colonel who has many medals on his chest to show how he has conquered bowlers all over the world” – Allan Donald
17. “On a train from Shimla to Delhi, there was a halt in one of the stations. The train stopped by for few minutes as usual. Sachin was nearing century, batting on 98.  The passengers, railway officials, everyone on the train waited for Sachin to complete the century. This Genius can stop time in India!” – Peter Roebuck
18. If I’ve to bowl to Sachin, I’ll bowl with my helmet on. He hits the ball so hard – Dennis Lillee
19. Sachin is a genius. I’m a mere mortal – Brian Lara
20. When you bowl at him you are not just trying to get him out, you are trying to impress him. “I want him to walk off thinking ‘that Flintoff, he’s all right isn’t he? I feel privileged to have played against him – Andrew Flintoff
21. Don’t bowl bad balls he hits the good ones for fours – Michael Kasprowicz
22. Why did you get out to such a silly shot? – Anjali Tendulkar wasn’t very happy with her husband’s shot selection
23. What we need is 10 Tendulkars – Paul Strang
24. Today, he showed the world why he is considered the best batsman around. Some of the shots he played were simply amazing. Earlier, opposing teams used to feel that Sachin’s dismissal meant they could win the game. Today, I feel that the Indian players, too, feel this way – Wasim Akram
25. You might pitch a ball on the off stump and think you have bowled a good ball and he walks across and hits it for two behind midwicket. His bat looks so heavy but he just waves it around like it’s a toothpick. – Brett Lee
26. I was fielding in the covers when Tendulkar came out to bat in his debut Test at Karachi. I still remember Waqar Younis was in peak form at that time. Tendulkar tried to drive Waqar through the covers off his very first ball in Test cricket but was beaten all ends up. But I walked to captain Imran Khan and told him ‘this kid looks very good’ and Imran agreed with me – Abdul Qadir
27. He has been in form longer than some of our guys have been alive – Daniel Vettori
28. I have joked before that there is a good chance that I might retire before Tendulkar – Mahendra Singh Dhoni
29. Commit all your crimes when Sachin is batting. They will go unnoticed because even the Lord is watching – From a fan at the SCG

Sachin was a great cricket player but not the greatest. He too failed couple twice in the most important World cup finals matches against Australia & Sri Lanka. They say cometh the hour cometh the man & had he scored runs in those finals he would have been greatest for me too. Those were thorns in flesh for Indian cricket fans. He failed to score more than 10 runs in the world cup finals against Australia , whereas another great Ricky Ponting scored match winning 140 in the most important match in a world cup. He also failed to score runs in 2011 WC finals against Sri Lanka thus failing his team & himself. The biggest blunder he committed was joining the epitome of corruption, Congress party just before the 2014 Lok Sabha elections knowing very well that this political party carried a baggage of 15 lakh crore worth scams! He failed to click again & Congress also lost badly , lastly his attendance was neither minimal at Rajya Sabha nor he raised too many questions for Indian Sportsman let alone cricketers. No one is perfect not even Sachin Tendulkar.

My goodness, this is such a gross exaggeration.  Sachin only made the team when he was 16 because the Indian team was so pathetic they had no choice but to recruit someone as young as him. No doubt he was a great player, but India is NO.1 in hero worship, they are desperate to worship someone and make him GOD. There have been so many other players in the World better than him, but the Indian BCCI needed to keep their fans excited so they hyped up Sachin so much. Virat is already a better ODI batsman, Younis Khan and Kumar Sangakarra are better tests batsman. Waqar and Wasim were the greatest bowling pair to ever live ! But we don't see movies and such gross exaggerations. Its amazing how simplistic Indians are, even Don Bradman or Gary Sobers never got such accolades. 
People also need to understand that the BCCI and the medis have hyped up SAchin so much that no matter what kind of movie you make about him it will make money. The movie might be rubbish itself but Sachin will make it a hit.
Also I feel it is a huge slap in the face of all those great cricketers who played along with Sachin. M. Azahruddin, Shahtri, Sidhu, Kumble, Harbhajan, Zaheer Khan and the list is very long.......Did they not carry hopes as well ? Did they not play for their country and sacrifice ? Ofcourse they did, why say 1 man carried the hopes of a billion people.

1: Named after legendary music director Sachin Dev Burman by his father
2: Grew his hair and tied a band around it to copy idol John McEnroe. Was even called 'McEnroe' by his friends. Admires Boris Becker, Pete Sampras, Roger Federer and Diego Maradona.
3: Wanted to be a fast bowler and even went to the MRF Pace Academy but head coach Dennis Lillee asked him to concentrate on batting.
4: Has scored big runs on Indian festivals like Gokulashtmi, Raksha Bandhan, Holi and Diwali
5: Loved to have 'I-can-eat-more-vada-pavs-than-you' competitions with cricket buddies Vinod Kambli and Salil Ankola
6: Loves sea food. Owned a restaurant.
7: Loves playing at Sydney Cricket Ground.
8: Loves Kishore Kumar and rock group Dire Straits. Was extremely possessive about his personal stereo.
9: A devout worshipper of Lord Ganesha, he often visits Siddhivinayak temple in the early hours of the morning.
10: Wears his left pad first. Has the Tri-colour pasted inside his kit bag.
11: Remembers every dismissal and even the bowler who dismissed him.
12: Likes to dunk his glucose biscuits into his tea and have them with a spoon.
13: He is ambidextrous. Bats with his right hand but autographs and eats with his left.
14: Used to sleep with his cricket gear on during his junior days.
15: Refused to shoot for a soft-drink ad that showed him smashing cricket balls with a fly swatter. He reportedly told film-maker Prahlad Kakkar, "That would make me greater than the game." The ad was modified: he hit the balls with a stump.
16: Loves to zoom across Mumbai in his swanky cars in the wee hours.
17: Fell from a tree one Sunday evening during his summer vacations, when the movie 'Guide' was showing on national TV. It infuriated brother (and mentor) Ajit, who packed him off to cricket coaching class as a punishment!
18: Came back from the four-month tour of Australia after the 1992 World Cup and turned up to play for Kirti College in April 1992.
19: Was without a bat contract during the 1996 World Cup in which he emerged highest run-getter. A famous tyre company promptly signed him on soon after.
20: His coach at Shardashram, Ramakant Achrekar, used to offer a one rupee coin as prize to any bowler who dismissed him. If he remained not out, the coin belonged to Sachin. Still has a good bunch of those coins.
21: Fielded for Pakistan as a substitute during a one-day practice match against India at the Brabourne in 1988.
22: Was a ball boy during the 1987 World Cup match between India and Zimbabwe at Wankhede.
23: The first ad he shot was for sticking plaster.
24: In school, he was once mistaken for a girl by good friend Atul Ranade because of his long curls
25: After watching Deewar and Zanjeer, he became a fan of Amitabh Bachchan
26: Played tennis-ball cricket and darts during rainbreaks
27: Sang and whistled with Vinod Kambli during their 664-run record stand in the Harris Shield in 1988 to avoid eye contact with the coach's assistant, who wanted to declare while the duo wanted to bat on.
28: Teammate Praveen Amre bought him his first pair of international quality cricket shoes.
29: Was a bully at school but was kind to cats and dogs. His first captain, Sunil Harshe, said that he loved to pick a fight. Every time he was introduced to someone, his first reaction was, 'Will I be able to beat him?'
30: Used to go fishing for tadpoles and guppy fishes in the stream that ran through the compound of Sahitya Sahwas, his apartment in Bandra East.
31: Once made his mother look for a frog bhaji recipe.
32: The nanny who looked after him is now universally called Sachuchi bai
33: Colony watchman's son Ramesh Pardhe, who was his playmate, said Sachin would ask him to dip a rubber ball in water and hurl it at him. He wanted to see the wet marks left on the bat to find out whether he had middled the ball correctly
34: An incorrigble prankster, he once put a hose pipe in Sourav Ganguly's room and turned on the tap. Ganguly awoke to find his gear floating. Calls Ganguly 'Babu Moshai'. Sourav calls him 'Chhota Babu'.
35: Great spinner of yarns. If he had a cut on his finger it was because it had been chopped by a helicopter flying low!
36: Sachin Tendulkar's debut Test also was legendary allrounder Kapil Dev's 100th.
37: Sachin faced his first ball in Tests from legendary Pak pacer Waqar Younis, who was also making his debut.
38: Sachin scored the first-ever double hundred in ODIs on February 24, 2010, 22 years to the day that Kambli and Sachin had put on 664.
39: He equalled Sunil Gavaskar's record of 34 Test hundreds and went past the record on the same date, December 10. His 34th ton came against Bangladesh in Dhaka on 2004 and the 35th was against Sri Lanka at the Kotla in 2005.
40: During an under-15 tour in Indore, he couldn't sleep and woke up in the middle of the night to shadow practise. As the flooring was wood-based, the noise that emanated from the bat hitting the flooring disturbed the other tenants. As the hotel manager went to complain to coach Vasu Paranjpe, he was ticked off by the coach and told to 'Go and bowl to him'.
50: *We people resisiding Globally LOVE you*

Sachin gets unnecessary hype and he has always overshadowed a much better player than him - Rahul Dravid! Sachin was lucky to be able to play for India at just 16 because there have been many players who have achieved even more than what Sachin did at 16 but they still have to wait till 22-23 to get a chance to play for India! That's simply because during Tendulkar's time the Indian team was really weak so he easily got into it whereas now the competition is so much that no matter how good u play u will not play for India before 22-23! Rahul Dravid was a much more dependable and consistent player and he always played for the team unlike Sachin who played for his individual records! Those who think Dravid was not good enough in ODI's let me tell u he has 10000+ ODI runs and has played close to 350 matches! Just go and have a look at his 22 ball 50 as well! Dravid deserved a much better farewell than what he got! Tendulkar always took the limelight away from Dravid! Anyone can play 200 tests if he makes his debut at such a young age! If u go and check the stats u will no that Dravid has had much more contribution in India's wins than Sachin especially in overseas! If u think that Dravid wasn't close to Sachin in ODI's just because he had only 12 centuries then let me tell u that u should check the countless half centuries Dravid has! Most of Sachin's big and important innings came in India! When he scored 241 against the Aussies in Sydney he didn't have to face Mcgrath and warne! Sachin just stretched his career for 2-3 years so that he could get that 100th century even if it came at the cost of wasting one batting position in the team! Dravid retired just because he had one bad overseas series and he thought it was time to give the youngsters a chance whereas Sachin kept on playing even though he wasn't really contributing to the team! He should have retired from ODI's after the World Cup itself! Look at the way players like Sangakkara Kallis and Dravid retired! Sangakkara retired from ODIs after scoring 4 back to back Hundreds in the World Cup! Kallis retired after scoring 100 in his last Test innings! Dravid had 5 Test  centuries in his last Test season which included 3 phenomenal 100s in England when no one else played well! Dravid has two Man of the Series Awards in England! Tendulkar just scored 2 or 3 centuries in last 25 tests whereas Dravid scored 6 or 7!  No one forced Sachin to retire because the Indians consider him God and so the BCCI didn't want to get abused by the fans! So he took full advantage of the situation and kept on playing just to score that one century! He was shameful enough to not even attend the Farewell ceremony of Dravid!
